ist/_/stevie%20nicks/#albums| title= Stevie Nicks > Artist > Official Charts | publisher=[[UK Albums Chart]]| accessdate=2013-09-08}}</ref>\n|3\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"USchart\">{{cite web|title=Allmusic: ''The Other Side of the Mirror'' : Charts & Awards : Billboard Albums|publisher=allmusic.com|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r14082/charts-awards|pure_url=yes}}|accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref>\n|10\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1989)\n! scope=\"col\"| Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Canadian Albums Chart<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6625&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=c6btf3r8hs459qqt5ln3o3dcv5|title=RPM Top 100 Albums of 1989|magazine=RPM|date=1989-12-23|accessdate=2014-04-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231000354/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6625&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=c6btf3r8hs459qqt5ln3o3dcv5|archivedate=2013-12-31}}</ref>\n|49\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|UK Albums Chart\n|93\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' 200\n|85\n|}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|title=The Other Side of the Mirror|artist=Stevie Nicks|type=album|award=Gold}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|title=The Other Side of the Mirror|artist=Stevie Nicks|type=album|award=Platinum}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Releases and promotions==\n*The UK 12-inch and CD single releases of \"Rooms on Fire\" feature an extended version of the song running at 9:00, and also include a live version of \"Has Anyone Ever Written Anything for You?\" recorded during the ''Rock a Little'' tour as featured in the video / DVD release of the Red Rocks concert in 1986. A limited edition of the UK 12-inch also came with a glossy, full-size, double-sided poster.\n*The single release of \"Long Way to Go\" (\"Two Kinds of Love\" in the US) features the non-album track \"Real Tears\", whilst the UK 12\" and CD single releases feature an extended remix of \"Long Way to Go\", running at 6:23 (and not 7:37 as stated on the label). The UK 12-inch release of \"Long Way to Go\" was also available in a limited edition gatefold sleeve.\n*The UK CD-single release of \"Whole Lotta Trouble\" features a live version of \"Beauty and the Beast\", recorded during the ''Rock a Little'' tour as featured in the video release of ''Live at Red Rocks''. A limited edition of the UK 12-inch release also came with a glossy, full-size, double-sided poster.\n*The Japanese CD release of the album includes the bonus track \"Has Anyone Ever Written Anything for You?\" recorded live during the ''Rock a Little'' tour\n*As a promotional giveaway in the UK, the album was released with a limited edition holographic sticker (the size of the sticker was dependent upon the format; vinyl album, cassette, CD). Album buyers were also given the opportunity to purchase a special display stand for the sticker by mail order.\n\n==Tour<ref>{{cite web|title= Stevie Nicks - The Other Side of the Mirror Tour 1989|url=https://stevienicks.info/tours/1989-the-other-side-of-the-mirror-tour/}}</ref>==\nSetlist:\n*\"Outside the Rain\"\n*\"[[Dreams (Fleetwood Mac song)|Dreams]]\"\n*\"Rooms on Fire\"\n*\"[[Gold Dust Woman]]\"\n*\"[[Stand Back (Stevie Nicks song)|Stand Back]]\"\n*\"Alice\"\n*\"No Spoken Word\"\n*\"How Still My Love\"\n*\"[[Beauty and the Beast (Stevie Nicks song)|Beauty and the Beast]]\"\n*\"Juliet\" (performed at some shows)\n*\"[[Talk to Me (Stevie Nicks song)|Talk to Me]]\" (performed at some shows)\n*\"Whole Lotta Trouble\"\n*\"Two Kinds of Love\"\n*\"[[Edge of Seventeen]]\"\n*\"[[Has Anyone Ever Written Anything for You?]]\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Stevie Nicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Other Side of the Mirror, The}}\n[[Category:Stevie Nicks albums]]\n[[Category:1989 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Rupert Hine]]\n[[Category:Music based on Alice in Wonderland]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records albums]]\n[[Category:EMI Records albums]]\n[[Category:Modern Records (1980) albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = The Other Side of the Mirror\n| type         = [[Album]]\n| artist       = [[Stevie Nicks]]\n| cover        = Stevie Nicks - The Other Side of the Mirror.png\n| alt          = \n| released     = May 11, 1989\n| recorded     = 1988\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = {{flat list|\n* [[Rock music|Rock]]\n* [[soft rock]]\n}}\n| length       = 56:10\n| label        = [[Modern Records (1980)|Modern]]\n| producer     = [[Rupert Hine]]\n| prev_title   = [[Rock a Little]]\n| prev_year    = 1985\n| next_title   = [[Timespace: The Best of Stevie Nicks]]\n| next_year    = 1991\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = The Other Side of the Mirror\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Rooms on Fire]]\n | single1date = April 21, 1989\n | single2     = [[Long Way to Go (Stevie Nicks song)|Long Way to Go]]\n | single2date = July 1989\n | single3     = Two Kinds of Love\n | single3date = August 11, 1989\n | single4     = [[Whole Lotta Trouble]]\n | single4date = October 13, 1989\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''The Other Side of the Mirror''''' is the fourth solo studio album by American singer and songwriter [[Stevie Nicks]]. Released on May 11, 1989 through the [[Modern Records (1980)|Modern]] label, the album was recorded in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], mixed in [[Buckinghamshire]], [[England]], and is loosely based around the theme of [[Lewis Carroll]]'s 1865 novel ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]''.\n\nThe album was a commercial success. It reached number ten on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], propelled by the hit single \"[[Rooms on Fire]]\" (US #16), and achieved Platinum status for selling in excess of 1,000,000 units. The album reached number three in the United Kingdom and was certified Gold there for sales in excess of 100,000 units,{{Certification Cite Ref|type=album|region=United Kingdom|title=The Other Side of the Mirror|artist=Stevie Nicks}} and is Nicks' highest charting album to date in various European countries including Germany, the Netherlands, Sweden and the UK.\n\n==Background==\nFollowing the huge success of [[Fleetwood Mac]]'s 1987 album ''[[Tango in the Night]]'' in the United Kingdom, ''The Other Side of the Mirror'' became Nicks' highest charting solo album there, reaching number three and spawning her first UK [[Top 40]] hit with \"[[Rooms on Fire]]\" (also #16), which Nicks performed on the [[BBC]] show ''[[Top of the Pops]]''. The album was certified gold in the UK for sales in excess of 100,000 copies. Her first, and so far only, solo tour of the UK and Europe (Sweden, France and the Netherlands), followed the album, as well as a tour of the United States, though Nicks has famously commented since that she has no recollection of the tours due to her increasing dependency on the prescribed tranquilizer [[Klonopin]] at that time.\n\nIn the US, \"Two Kinds of Love\" was released as a [[Single (music)|single]], featuring vocals by [[Bruce Hornsby]] and instrumental interlude by [[Kenny G]], which became Nicks' first single to fail to chart, missing both the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'']] and [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] charts completely. \"Long Way to Go\" gained substantial airplay, making [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']]'s [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock]] chart, and also made the Top 75 on the [[UK Singles Chart]], as did \"Whole Lotta Trouble\". Promotional [[music video]]s were shot for \"Rooms on Fire\" and \"Whole Lotta Trouble\". The former was released in two slightly different edits, while the \"Whole Lotta Trouble\" video was shot during the American leg of Nicks' tour at the Summit Arena in Houston, Texas.\n\nAn earlier, instrumental version of the song \"Juliet\" (entitled \"Book of Miracles\") was released by Fleetwood Mac in 1987 as the B-side to \"[[Seven Wonders (song)|Seven Wonders]]\", while \u201cOoh My Love\u201d had been demo-ed for ''Tango in the Night'' but was ultimately shelved. The song \"[[Cry Wolf (Laura Branigan song)|Cry Wolf]]\" was originally recorded by American singer [[Laura Branigan]] for her fifth studio album ''[[Touch (Laura Branigan album)|Touch]]'' (1987).\n\n[[Modern Records (1980)|Modern Records]] also released a special long-form interview video on the making-of the album entitled, \"Reflections from the Other Side of the Mirror\", which contained newly filmed material shot by Herbert Worthington III.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Stevie-Nicks-Reflections-From-The-Other-Side-Of-The-Mirror/release/6395359|title=Stevie Nicks - Reflections From The Other Side Of The Mirror|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2018-01-11}}</ref> However, it was limited to a worldwide release of 10,000 albums and only 500 VHS releases.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|first=Alex|last=Henderson|title=Allmusic Review: ''The Other Side of the Mirror'' |url={{Allmusic|class=album |id=r14083 |pure_url=yes}}  |website=Allmusic.com |accessdate=2014-04-13}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|2|4}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-06-08/features/8902070815_1_star-fleetwood-mac-stevie-nicks|last=Silverman|first=David|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|title=Stevie Nicks Other Side of the Mirror|date=1989-06-08|accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Deseret News]]''\n| rev3score = (Positive)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/54180/MIRROR-REFLECTS-NICKS-TALENTS---SOLO-OR-OTHERWISE.html?pg=all|first=Jerry|last=Spangler|work=nytimes.com|publisher=The New York Times|title=\n`MIRROR' REFLECTS NICKS' TALENTS - SOLO OR OTHERWISE|date=1989-06-06|accessdate=2013-08-31}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-05-28/entertainment/ca-1371_1_stevie-nicks-all-star-cast-bruce-hornsby|last=Hochman|first=Steve|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|title= Record Rack: STEVIE NICKS \"The Other Side of the Mirror.\" Modern/Atlantic|date=1989-05-28|accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''\n| rev5score = (Mixed)<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20120648,00.html|magazine=People|title=Picks and Pans Review: ''Rock  A Little''|date=1985-01-13|accessdate=2013-11-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429205203/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20120648,00.html|archivedate=2014-04-29}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/stevienicks/albums/album/201616/review/5941240/the_other_side_of_the_mirror Rolling Stone review]</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| title1   = [[Rooms on Fire]]\n| length1  = 4:35\n| writer1  = {{hlist|Stevie Nicks|[[Rick Nowels]]}}\n| title2   = [[Long Way to Go (Stevie Nicks song)|Long Way to Go]]\n| length2  = 4:06\n| writer2  = {{hlist|Nicks|Nowels|Charles Judge}}\n| title3   = Two Kinds of Love\n| note3    = with [[Bruce Hornsby]]\n| length3  = 4:46\n| writer3  = {{hlist|Nicks|[[Rupert Hine]]|Nowels}}\n| title4   = Ooh My Love\n| length4  = 5:02\n| writer4  = {{hlist|Nicks|Nowels}}\n| title5   = Ghosts\n| writer5  = {{hlist|Nicks|[[Mike Campbell (musician)|Mike Campbell]]}}\n| length5  = 4:54\n| title6   = [[Whole Lotta Trouble]]\n| length6  = 4:58\n| writer6  = {{hlist|Nicks|Campbell}}\n| title7   = Fire Burning\n| length7  = 3:16\n| writer7  = {{hlist|Nicks|Campbell|Hine}}\n| title8   = [[Cry Wolf (Laura Branigan song)|Cry Wolf]]\n| length8  = 4:12\n| writer8  = [[Jude Johnstone]]\n| title9   = Alice\n| length9  = 5:50\n| writer9  = {{hlist|Nicks|Hine}}\n| title10  = Juliet\n| length10 = 4:55\n| writer10 = Nicks\n| title11   = Doing the Best I Can (Escape from Berlin)\n| length11  = 5:36\n| writer11  = Nicks\n| title12  = [[I Still Miss Someone]] (Blue Eyes)\n| length12 = 4:08\n| writer12 = {{hlist|[[Johnny Cash]]|Roy Cash Jr.}}\n| total_length = 56:06\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n*Stevie Nicks \u2013 vocals, percussion, tambourine\n*Sharon Celani \u2013 backing vocals\n*Lori Nicks \u2013 backing vocals\n*[[Rupert Hine]] \u2013 keyboards, percussion, drums\n*[[Mike Campbell (musician)|Mike Campbell]] \u2013 guitar\n*[[Kenny G]] \u2013 saxophone\n*[[Geoff Dugmore]] \u2013 drums\n*Gary Grant \u2013 horns\n*[[Jerry Hey]] \u2013 horns\n*Larry Williams \u2013 horns\n*[[Marc Russo]] \u2013 horns\n*[[Bruce Hornsby]] \u2013 piano, vocals\n*Vail Johnson \u2013 bass guitar\n*Kelly Johnston\t\u2013 whistle\n*[[Tony Levin]] \u2013 bass\n*[[Jerry Marotta]] \u2013 drums\n*Derek Murphy \u2013 bass\n*[[Rick Nowels]] \u2013 keyboards, guitar, backing vocals\n*[[Waddy Wachtel]] \u2013 guitar\n*[[Jamie West-Oram]] \u2013 guitar\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1989)\n! scope=\"col\"| Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[ARIA Charts|Australian ARIA Album Chart]]<ref>{{cite web| title = australian-charts.com The Other Side of the Mirror| publisher = [[Australian Recording Industry Association]]| url = http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Stevie+Nicks&titel=The+Other+Side+Of+The+Mirror&cat=a|format=ASP| accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref>\n|8\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[RPM (magazine)|Canadian RPM Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6399&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=c6btf3r8hs459qqt5ln3o3dcv5|title=Top Albums/CDs - Volume 50, 