a|language=German|work=Hung Medien|format=ASP|publisher=Swiss Music Charts|accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref>\n|79\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[UK Albums Chart]] <ref name=\"UKchart\">{{cite web| url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/stevie%20nicks/#albums| title= Stevie Nicks > Artist > Official Charts | publisher=[[UK Albums Chart]]| accessdate=2013-09-08}}</ref>\n|3\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"USchart\">{{cite web|title=Allmusic: ''The Other Side of the Mirror'' : Charts & Awards : Billboard Albums|publisher=allmusic.com|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r14082/charts-awards|pure_url=yes}}|accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref>\n|10\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1989)\n! scope=\"col\"| Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Canadian Albums Chart<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6625&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=c6btf3r8hs459qqt5ln3o3dcv5|title=RPM Top 100 Albums of 1989|magazine=RPM|date=1989-12-23|accessdate=2014-04-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231000354/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6625&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=c6btf3r8hs459qqt5ln3o3dcv5|archivedate=2013-12-31}}</ref>\n|49\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|UK Albums Chart\n|93\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' 200\n|85\n|}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|title=The Other Side of the Mirror|artist=Stevie Nicks|type=album|award=Gold}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|title=The Other Side of the Mirror|artist=Stevie Nicks|type=album|award=Platinum}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Releases and promotions==\n*The UK 12-inch and CD single releases of \"Rooms on Fire\" feature an extended version of the song running at 9:00, and also include a live version of \"Has Anyone Ever Written Anything for You?\" recorded during the ''Rock a Little'' tour as featured in the video / DVD release of the Red Rocks concert in 1986. A limited edition of the UK 12-inch also came with a glossy, full-size, double-sided poster.\n*The single release of \"Long Way to Go\" (\"Two Kinds of Love\" in the US) features the non-album track \"Real Tears\", whilst the UK 12\" and CD single releases feature an extended remix of \"Long Way to Go\", running at 6:23 (and not 7:37 as stated on the label). The UK 12-inch release of \"Long Way to Go\" was also available in a limited edition gatefold sleeve.\n*The UK CD-single release of \"Whole Lotta Trouble\" features a live version of \"Beauty and the Beast\", recorded during the ''Rock a Little'' tour as featured in the video release of ''Live at Red Rocks''. A limited edition of the UK 12-inch release also came with a glossy, full-size, double-sided poster.\n*The Japanese CD release of the album includes the bonus track \"Has Anyone Ever Written Anything for You?\" recorded live during the ''Rock a Little'' tour\n*As a promotional giveaway in the UK, the album was released with a limited edition holographic sticker (the size of the sticker was dependent upon the format; vinyl album, cassette, CD). Album buyers were also given the opportunity to purchase a special display stand for the sticker by mail order.\n\n==Tour<ref>{{cite web|title= Stevie Nicks - The Other Side of the Mirror Tour 1989|url=https://stevienicks.info/tours/1989-the-other-side-of-the-mirror-tour/}}</ref>==\nSetlist:\n*\"Outside the Rain\"\n*\"[[Dreams (Fleetwood Mac song)|Dreams]]\"\n*\"Rooms on Fire\"\n*\"[[Gold Dust Woman]]\"\n*\"[[Stand Back (Stevie Nicks song)|Stand Back]]\"\n*\"Alice\"\n*\"No Spoken Word\"\n*\"How Still My Love\"\n*\"[[Beauty and the Beast (Stevie Nicks song)|Beauty and the Beast]]\"\n*\"Juliet\" (performed at some shows)\n*\"[[Talk to Me (Stevie Nicks song)|Talk to Me]]\" (performed at some shows)\n*\"Whole Lotta Trouble\"\n*\"Two Kinds of Love\"\n*\"[[Edge of Seventeen]]\"\n*\"[[Has Anyone Ever Written Anything for You?]]\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Stevie Nicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Other Side of the Mirror, The}}\n[[Category:Stevie Nicks albums]]\n[[Category:1989 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Rupert Hine]]\n[[Category:Music based on Alice in Wonderland]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records albums]]\n[[Category:EMI Records albums]]\n[[Category:Modern Records (1980) albums]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Other_Side_of_the_Mirror_(album)"}
{"title_page": "Archeological Site 4-SK-4", "text_new": "{{short description|Prehistoric human settlement  location}}\n{{Infobox historic site\n  | name           = Archeological Site 4-SK-4\n  | image          = Indian Tom Lake Rd.jpeg\n  | caption        = Location of Nightfire Island on a private property adjacent to Otey Ridge in the background\n  | nearest_city   = [[Tulelake, California]]\n  | locmapin       = California#USA\n  | area           = {{convert|2.5|acre}}\n}}\n'''Archeological Site 4-SK-4''', in [[Tulelake, California]], near [[Macdoel, California]], is a stratified [[archeological site]] that was a hunter-gatherer village on the west shores of the [[Lower Klamath Lake]].<ref name=\"ussite\">{{cite web|title=Notice of Inventory Completion: University of Oregon, Oregon State Museum of Anthropology, Eugene, OR|url=https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2009/02/02/E9-2147/notice-of-inventory-completion-university-of-oregon-oregon-state-museum-of-anthropology-eugene-or|accessdate=April 10, 2020 |author=Federal Register, The Daily Journal of the United States Governement||date=February 2, 2009 |}}</ref> The site is located in the heart of the [[Klamath Basin]] wetlands, west of [[Indian Tom Lake]].<ref name=\"site\">{{cite web|last=Garfinkel |first=Alan P. |title=Culture Crisis and Rock Art Intensification:  Numic Ghost Dance Paintings and Coso Representational Petroglyphs |url=http://www.petroglyphs.us/article_culture_crisis_and_rock_art_intensification.htm |accessdate=April 15, 2013 |author2=Geron Marcom |author3=Robert A. Schiffman |date=November 26, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506092308/http://www.petroglyphs.us/article_culture_crisis_and_rock_art_intensification.htm |archivedate=May 6, 2013 }}</ref> It has also been known as '''Nightfire Island'''<ref>{{cite book |last= Hughes|first= R E|author-link= |date= 1986|title= Diachronic variability in obsidian procurement patterns in northeastern California and southcentral Oregon|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Bvjg2LypUowC|location= |publisher= Univ of California Press|page= |isbn=}}</ref> and as '''Sheepy Island'''. Modern Modocs have called the island ''Shapasheni'' (Shapash /xpni),<ref name=\"geoarch\" /> meaning \"where the sun and moon live\",<ref name=\"Murguia\">{{cite book |last= Murgu\u00eda|first= Alejandro |author-link= |date= 2002|title= The Medicine of Memory: A Mexica Clan in California|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=DVZfAgAAQBAJ|location= |publisher= University of Texas Press|page= 154-155|isbn=0292778708}}</ref> or \"home of the sun and the moon.<ref>{{cite book |last= Doty|first= Thomas |author-link= |date= 2002|title= Doty Meets Coyote|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=LhuUCwAAQBAJ|location= |publisher= Blackstone Publishing|page= |isbn=1504708334}}</ref> \n\nPrehistorically, it served as a village camp on a wetland man-made mound and as a ceremonial site.<ref name=howe>Howe, 8-9</ref> The site shows evidence of human occupancy from the peak of the [[Holocene climatic optimum|Hypsithermal era]], approximately 7,000 years ago.<ref>Johnson, L. (1969). Obsidian hydration rate for the Klamath Basin of California and Oregon. Science, 165(3900), 1354-1356.</ref> Archeologist have unearthed three villages one on top of the other through the centuries.<ref>{{cite book |last= Kittredge|first= William |author-link= |date= 2000|title= Balancing Water: Restoring the Klamath Basin|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=U89OpWh0itoC|location= |publisher= University of California Press|page= 167|isbn=0520213149}}</ref> [[Obsidian]] [[arrowhead]]s are frequent finds, whose varieties include Northern Sided Notched, [[Elko point|Elko type corner notched]], and Gunther type points.<ref>Justice, N. D. (2002). [https://books.google.com/books?id=kzrfXiifiToC Stone Age spear and arrow points of California and the Great Basin] Indiana University Press. Page 174</ref> \n\nExcavations and sampling started in 1966 by Klamath educator Carrol Howe. The site was described by Garth Sampson in a 1985 publication of the [[University of Oregon]], located in [[Eugene, Oregon]].<ref name=\"geoarch\">{{cite journal|last=Sampson|first=C. Garth|title=Nightfire Island: Later holocene lakemarsh adaptation on the western edge of the great basin|journal=Geoarcheology|year=1985|volume=2|pages=247|url=https://escholarship.org/content/qt5wq3p6dd/qt5wq3p6dd.pdf|accessdate=April 5, 2020|doi=}}</ref> \n\n==History==\nHuman occupation of the Klamath Basin areas may have begun around 6000 BCE.<ref name=\"geoarch\" /> Settlement by [[Modoc people]] on the banks of Sheepy Creek is likely to have begun approximately 4000 years [[Common Era|BCE]],<ref name=\"grayson\" /> shortly after the eruption of [[Mount Mazama]], as evidenced by a layer of volcanic ash on the lake bed just below the layer that marks the appearance of a new village.<ref name=howe /> \n\nThe shallow water level of the marsh, the clay loam, and the basalt rubble basin extended all around and over this area afforded only a weak foundation for settlement. To compensate, inhabitants carried in rocks to strengthen the village's foundation. After centuries of this procedure, they had built an island of an area approximately {{Convert|2.5|acre||abbr=}}. \n\nSurrounded by marshlands, the villagers could fish and hunt [[Anseriformes|waterfowl]].<ref>Kittredge, W. (2000). [https://books.google.com/books?id=U89OpWh0itoC Balancing water: restoring the Klamath Basin]. Univ of California Press. Page 176</ref> The springs nearest to Nightfire Island are geothermal waters, adding to the comfort of the villagers. During the dry months, the receding water levels allowed for the establishment of a secure hunting station. Charcoal remains show evidence of cooking pits and cremated burial sites within the island. Bones show an early abundance of duck with additional diversity appearing in later years.<ref name=\"geoarch\" />\n \nWaterfowl droppings within layers of the excavation site show that there were times where the site was abandoned for several hundred years, probably because of the rising of the levels of Indian Tom Lake, climate change during the hot and dry middle [[Holocene]], or changes in the Keno fault.<ref name=\"grayson\">Grayson, D. K. (1976). A note on the prehistoric avifauna of the Lower Klamath Basin. The Auk, 93(4), 830-833.</ref> When water levels receded, occupation resumed with the appearance of black charcoal levels from cooking and cremation fires.<ref name=\"howe\" />\n\n==Archeology==\nExcavations of archeological site 4-SK-4 have produced large collections of bird, mammal, and fish bones, large amounts of obsidian technology (particularly Elko points), bone artifacts, mortars and other stone artifacts as well as other cultural detritus.<ref name=\"grayson\" /><ref name=\"Murguia\" /> These occupational debris reach a maximum of 3 meters deep. The lower stratum is [[Lake|lacustrine]], waterway [[diatom]]-rich silt from the original lake floor present during the first occupation of the site. From there, the strata consist of a series of [[silt]], streamland and [[loam]] forming a [[duripan]] horizon.<ref>{{cite web|title=Modoc Series|url=https://soilseries.sc.egov.usda.gov/OSD_Docs/M/MODOC.html|accessdate=April 14, 2020 |author=USDA Soil Series Descriptions and Series Classification|date=August 2004}}</ref>\n\nVillagers cooked small animals by boiling them in baskets, while larger animals were cooked in rock roasting ovens primarily composed of large basalt rocks. Along with oven rocks, other rocks included broken fragments of [[mortar and pestle]]s and banded stones used for weights. Banded rocks are generally used for outdoor support such as tying down canoes.<ref>{{cite book |last= Carlisle|first= Rodney P. |author-link= |date= 2007|title= Native America from Prehistory to First Contact|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=J7FZggSz3eAC|location= |publisher= ABC-CLIO|page= 177|isbn=1851098291}}</ref> On Nightfire Island, banded rocks may have been used for indoor weights since they were found inside the houses and in roasting pits.<ref>Howe, p. 64</ref> The number of these rocks and their weight exceeds the traditional canoe weights and even the weights used by the [[Modoc people]] for the balsa-type rafts. The banded rocks from Nightfire Island show signs of burning mixed with charcoal from cooking fires.<ref>Howe, p. 67</ref> Some stones were used for boiling food in basketry by placing the hot basalt or lava stones into tightly packed woven water-filled baskets.<ref>{{cite book |last= The Library of Native Americans|first= |author-link= |date= 2003|title= The Modoc of California and Oregon|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=6AjymTpzRTUC|location= |publisher= The [[Rosen Publishing]] Group|page= 19|isbn=1404226605}}</ref>\n\nThe presence of buffalo hide on Nightfire Island suggest the village hunters used obsidian and [[spear-thrower]]s. The most common arrow point found on the site is the [[Cascade point|Cascade-type]]. Additionally, the excavation has produced several [[Lithic reduction|pressure-flaking]] tools made of bone and antler used for projectiles, especially before the bow and arrow were in use.<ref name=\"Howe72\">Howe, p. 72</ref> Stone anvils from the excavation had single and bilateral worn out pits used for [[knapping]] the obsidian to break the [[spall]]s from the rock.<ref>{{cite book |last= Hranicky|first= Wm Jack |author-link= |date= 2013|title= Archaeological Concepts, Techniques, and Terminology for American Prehistoric Lithic Technology|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=PSDtkmsHIEsC|location= |publisher= AuthorHouse|page=82, 277 |isbn=1481751743}}</ref> The large amount of anvils found on Nightfire Island suggest they were used for other purposes than knapping, including cracking bones. The side pits are not worn out consistent with the use as a maul or for pounding food.<ref name=\"Howe72\" /> \n\nWhile Modocs of the [[Great Basin]] had chipped-stone crescents or lunates,<ref>{{cite book |last= Justice|first= Noel D. |date= 2002|title= Stone Age Spear and Arrow Points of California and the Great Basin|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=kzrfXiifiToC|location= |publisher= Indiana University Press|page=116|isbn=0253108837}}</ref><ref>University of California Archaeological Survey, & Berkeley. Archaeological Research Facility. (1960). [https://books.google.com/books?id=0rKVdi0HrusC Reports of the University of California Archaeological Survey]. University of California Archaeological Survey, Department of Anthropology, University of California. p. 44.</ref> their presence has not been confirmed on Nightfire Island. Some smaller versions have been excavated but they are of a different shape and material.<ref name=\"Howe33\">Howe, p. 33 </ref> An increase in small, stemmed and cornr notched arrowheads have been discovered on layers of approximately 2,500 years BCE which corresponds to the peak in the dabbling duck remains and the adoption of the bow and arrow. \n\n===Culture===\nExcavations have unearthed structures that suggest buildings similar to [[sweat lodge]]s on Nightfire Island. Carbon-14 dated to approximately 1,500 years ago, these would be the oldest remains of a sweat lodge.<ref name=\"Murguia\" />\n\nA higher than usual frequency of neuronal malformations in remains discovered within Nightfire Island suggest tentatively that [[inbreeding]] might have occurred.<ref>Bennett, K. A. (1972). [https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/ajpa.1330360315 Lumbo\u2010sacral malformations and spina bifida occulta in a group of proto\u2010historic Modoc Indians]. ''American Journal of Physical Anthropology'', 36(3), 435-439.</ref> Studies of skeletal remains also revealed an unusually large and deep fossae lateral in the 1st and 2nd sacral tuberosities, suggesting a very strong postural ligament attachment.<ref>de la Mata, R. C., & Bonavia, D. (1980). [https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1086/202506?journalCode=ca Lumbosacral malformations and spina bifida in a Peruvian preceramic child]. ''Current Anthropology'', 21(4), 515-516.</ref>\n\nNightfire Modocs were prominent waterfowl hunters. While rainfall was not consistent, the alkali open marshes held in place by block-fault ridges provided a rich habitat for local and migratory waterfowl. In the Fall [[Northern pintail|pintails]] and [[mallard]]s arrived first along the [[Pacific Flyway]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Northern Pintail |url=http://www.seattleaudubon.org/birdweb/bird/northern_pintail|accessdate=April 14, 2020 |author=Seattle Audubon Society|date=February 2, 2009 |}}</ref> and later in the season [[American wigeon|baldpates]] and [[canvasback]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=American Wigeon|url=http://www.ducks.org/hunting/waterfowl-id/american-wigeon|accessdate=April 14, 2020 |author=Ducks Unlimited|date=|}}</ref> [[Coot]] and the [[common merganser]] were common as overwinter birds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Common mergansers: The piscivorous divers|url=https://www.heraldandnews.com/outdoors/common-mergansers-the-piscivorous-divers/article_56d9b09e-b057-50e1-bb86-efde38509c97.html|accessdate=April 14, 2020 |author=Gary Vequist (Herald and News|date=21 Dec 2018}}</ref> On the northern direction, white [[Snow goose|snow geese]] arrived first and white [[Greater white-fronted goose|fronted geese]] were among the latest to fly by. Nightfire Island soils didn't contain egg shells,<ref> Howe, p. 36-37</ref> however residents took advantage of bird-nesting season for the stability of their life cycle.\n\n===Paleontology finds===\nAnalysis of samples from Nightfire Island show that residents ate a great variety of birds: ''[[Podiceps]]'' spp., ''[[Cygnus (genus)|Cygnus]]'' spp., ''[[Branta]]'' spp., ''[[Anas]]'' spp., ''[[Aythya]]'' spp., ''[[Bucephala (bird)|Bucephala]]'' spp., and ''[[Mergus]]'' spp.<ref>Howe, p. 40</ref> Additionally, bones of eagles, owls and raven were also found among the kitchen [[midden]].<ref name=\"grayson\" /> Deeper levels of the marshy lake allowed for a higher quantity of waterfowl during the [[Common Era|CE]].\n\nThe bird life of Nightfire Island includes the following species dated by [[Radiocarbon dating|radiocarbon]] determinations:<ref name=\"grayson\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Dates and species defined by number of identified specimens\n|-\n!from 4000-3000 BC\n!from 3000-2200 BC\n!from 2020 BC-AD 0\n!from 0-1400 AD\n|-\n|[[Common loon]] (0)\n|[[Common loon]] (0)\n|[[Common loon]] (5)\n|[[Common loon]] (17)\n|-\n|[[Horned grebe]] (0)\n|[[Horned grebe]] (1)\n|[[Horned grebe]] (5)\n|[[Horned grebe]] (25)\n|-\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (1)\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (5)\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (15)\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (10)\n|-\n|[[Western grebe]] (1)\n|[[Western grebe]] (2)\n|[[Western grebe]] (28)\n|[[Western grebe]] (280)\n|-\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (5)\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (9)\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (27)\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (51)\n|-\n|[[American white pelican]] (0)\n|[[American white pelican]] (1)\n|[[American white pelican]] (4)\n|[[American white pelican]] (0)\n|-\n|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (1)\n|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (0)\n|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (0)\n|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (6)\n|-\n|[[Great blue heron]] (1)\n|[[Great blue heron]] (0)\n|[[Great blue heron]] (0)\n|[[Great blue heron]] (4)\n|-\n|[[Black-crowned night heron]] (0)\n|[[Black-crowned night heron]] (1)\n|[[Black-crowned night heron]] (3)\n|[[Black-crowned night heron]] (2)\n|-\n|[[American bittern]] (1)\n|[[American bittern]] (1)\n|[[American bittern]] (1)\n|[[American bittern]] (1)\n|-\n|[[Tundra swan]] (1)\n|[[Tundra swan]] (6)\n|[[Tundra swan]] (1)\n|[[Tundra swan]] (6)\n|-\n|[[Trumpeter swan]] (1)\n|[[Trumpeter swan]] (0)\n|[[Trumpeter swan]] (2)\n|[[Trumpeter swan]] (1)\n|-\n|[[Canada goose]] (2)\n|[[Canada goose]] (4)\n|[[Canada goose]] (16)\n|[[Canada goose]] (6)\n|-\n|[[Mallard|Mallard duck]] (3)\n|[[Mallard|Mallard duck]] (45)\n|[[Mallard|Mallard duck]] (95)\n|[[Mallard|Mallard duck]] (52)\n|-\n|[[Gadwall]], [[Northern pintail|pintails]],<br> [[American wigeon]],<br> and/or [[Northern shoveler|shovelers]] (3)\n|[[Gadwall]], [[Northern pintail|pintails]],<br> [[American wigeon]],<br> and/or [[Northern shoveler|shovelers]] (19)\n|[[Gadwall]], [[Northern pintail|pintails]],<br> [[American wigeon]],<br> and/or [[Northern shoveler|shovelers]] (41)\n||[[Gadwall]], [[Northern pintail|pintails]],<br> [[American wigeon]],<br> and/or [[Northern shoveler|shovelers]] (51)\n|-\n|[[Green-winged teal]], [[Blue-winged teal|Blue-winged]]<br> [[Blue-winged teal|teal]] and/or  [[Cinnamon teal]] (1)\n|[[Green-winged teal]], [[Blue-winged teal|Blue-winged]]<br> [[Blue-winged teal|teal]] and/or  [[Cinnamon teal]] (2)\n||[[Green-winged teal]], [[Blue-winged teal|Blue-winged]]<br> [[Blue-winged teal|teal]] and/or  [[Cinnamon teal]] (36)\n|[[Green-winged teal]], [[Blue-winged teal|Blue-winged]]<br> [[Blue-winged teal|teal]] and/or  [[Cinnamon teal]] (14)\n|-\n|[[Ring-necked duck]] (0)\n|[[Ring-necked duck]] (0)\n|[[Ring-necked duck]] (1)\n|[[Ring-necked duck]] (112)\n|-\n|[[Canvasback]] (0)\n|[[Canvasback]] (2)\n|[[Canvasback]] (15)\n|[[Canvasback]] (131)\n|-\n|[[Greater scaup]], [[Redhead (bird)|Redhead duck]],</br> and/or [[Lesser scaup]] (4)\n|[[Greater scaup]], [[Redhead (bird)|Redhead duck]],</br> and/or [[Lesser scaup]] (7)\n|[[Greater scaup]], [[Redhead (bird)|Redhead duck]],</br> and/or [[Lesser scaup]] (12)\n|[[Greater scaup]], [[Redhead (bird)|Redhead duck]],</br> and/or [[Lesser scaup]] (3)\n|-\n|[[Common goldeneye]] (0)\n|[[Common goldeneye]] (0)\n|[[Common goldeneye]] (2)\n|[[Common goldeneye]] (0)\n|- \n|[[Bufflehead]] (3)\n|[[Bufflehead]] (3)\n|[[Bufflehead]] (13)\n|[[Bufflehead]] (25)\n|-\n|[[Ruddy duck]] (17)\n|[[Ruddy duck]] (9)\n|[[Ruddy duck]] (48)\n|[[Ruddy duck]] (92)\n|-\n|[[Hooded merganser]] (0)\n|[[Hooded merganser]] (0)\n|[[Hooded merganser]] (3)\n|[[Hooded merganser]] (103)\n|-\n|[[Common merganser]] (8)\n|[[Common merganser]] (18)\n|[[Common merganser]] (24)\n|[[Common merganser]] (111)\n|-\n|[[Red-breasted merganser]]) (0)\n|[[Red-breasted merganser]]) (1)\n|[[Red-breasted merganser]]) (0)\n|[[Red-breasted merganser]]) (1)\n|-\n|[[Golden eagle]] (1)\n|[[Golden eagle]] (1)\n|[[Golden eagle]] (61)\n|[[Golden eagle]] (0)\n|-\n|[[Bald eagle]]s (3)\n|[[Bald eagle]]s (3)\n|[[Bald eagle]]s (1)\n|[[Bald eagle]]s (1)\n|-\n|[[Hen harrier]] (0)\n|[[Hen harrier]] (0)\n|[[Hen harrier]] (1)\n|[[Hen harrier]] (1)\n|-\n|[[Greater sage-grouse]] (1)\n|[[Greater sage-grouse]] (0)\n|[[Greater sage-grouse]] (4)\n|[[Greater sage-grouse]] (0)\n|-\n|[[American coot]] (20)\n|[[American coot]] (53)\n|[[American coot]] (387)\n|[[American coot]] (1220)\n|-\n|[[Killdeer]] (0)\n|[[Killdeer]] (1)\n|[[Killdeer]] (0)\n|[[Killdeer]] (0)\n|-\n|[[European herring gull]] (0)\n|[[European herring gull]] (0)\n|[[European herring gull]] (0)\n|[[European herring gull]] (1)\n|-\n|[[Great horned owl]]s (0)\n|[[Great horned owl]]s (0)\n|[[Great horned owl]]s (0)\n|[[Great horned owl]]s (1)\n|-\n|[[Snowy owl]] (0)\n|[[Snowy owl]] (0)\n|[[Snowy owl]] (1)\n|[[Snowy owl]] (0)\n|-\n|[[Short-eared owl]] (0)\n|[[Short-eared owl]] (0)\n|[[Short-eared owl]] (0)\n|[[Short-eared owl]] (1)\n|-\n|[[Common raven]] (0)\n|[[Common raven]] (0)\n|[[Common raven]] (0)\n|[[Common raven]] (1)\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last= Howe|first= Carrol B|author-link= |date= 1979|title= Ancient Modocs of California and Oregon|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=qi0aAQAAIAAJ|location= |publisher= Binford & Mort|page= |isbn=}}\n\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 6th millennium BC]]\n[[Category:1966 archaeological discoveries]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in California]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Siskiyou County, California]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Siskiyou County, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Prehistoric human settlement  location}}\n{{Infobox historic site\n  | name           = Archeological Site 4-SK-4\n  | image          = Indian Tom Lake Rd.jpeg\n  | caption        = Location of Nightfire Island on a private property adjacent to Otey Ridge in the background\n  | nearest_city   = [[Tulelake, California]]\n  | locmapin       = California#USA\n  | area           = {{convert|2.5|acre}}\n}}\n'''Archeological Site 4-SK-4''', in [[Tulelake, California]], near [[Macdoel, California]], is a stratified [[archeological site]] that was a hunter-gatherer village on the west shores of the [[Lower Klamath Lake]].<ref name=\"ussite\">{{cite web|title=Notice of Inventory Completion: University of Oregon, Oregon State Museum of Anthropology, Eugene, OR|url=https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2009/02/02/E9-2147/notice-of-inventory-completion-university-of-oregon-oregon-state-museum-of-anthropology-eugene-or|accessdate=April 10, 2020 |author=Federal Register, The Daily Journal of the United States Governement||date=February 2, 2009 |}}</ref> The site is located in the heart of the [[Klamath Basin]] wetlands, west of [[Indian Tom Lake]].<ref name=\"site\">{{cite web|last=Garfinkel |first=Alan P. |title=Culture Crisis and Rock Art Intensification:  Numic Ghost Dance Paintings and Coso Representational Petroglyphs |url=http://www.petroglyphs.us/article_culture_crisis_and_rock_art_intensification.htm |accessdate=April 15, 2013 |author2=Geron Marcom |author3=Robert A. Schiffman |date=November 26, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506092308/http://www.petroglyphs.us/article_culture_crisis_and_rock_art_intensification.htm |archivedate=May 6, 2013 }}</ref> It has also been known as '''Nightfire Island'''<ref>{{cite book |last= Hughes|first= R E|author-link= |date= 1986|title= Diachronic variability in obsidian procurement patterns in northeastern California and southcentral Oregon|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Bvjg2LypUowC|location= |publisher= Univ of California Press|page= |isbn=}}</ref> and as '''Sheepy Island'''. Modern Modocs have called the island ''Shapasheni'' (Shapash /xpni),<ref name=\"geoarch\" /> meaning \"where the sun and moon live\",<ref name=\"Murguia\">{{cite book |last= Murgu\u00eda|first= Alejandro |author-link= |date= 2002|title= The Medicine of Memory: A Mexica Clan in California|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=DVZfAgAAQBAJ|location= |publisher= University of Texas Press|page= 154-155|isbn=0292778708}}</ref> or \"home of the sun and the moon.<ref>{{cite book |last= Doty|first= Thomas |author-link= |date= 2002|title= Doty Meets Coyote|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=LhuUCwAAQBAJ|location= |publisher= Blackstone Publishing|page= |isbn=1504708334}}</ref> \n\nPrehistorically, it served as a village camp on a wetland man-made mound and as a ceremonial site.<ref name=howe>Howe, 8-9</ref> The site shows evidence of human occupancy from the peak of the [[Holocene climatic optimum|Hypsithermal era]], approximately 7,000 years ago.<ref>Johnson, L. (1969). Obsidian hydration rate for the Klamath Basin of California and Oregon. Science, 165(3900), 1354-1356.</ref> Archeologist have unearthed three villages one on top of the other through the centuries.<ref>{{cite book |last= Kittredge|first= William |author-link= |date= 2000|title= Balancing Water: Restoring the Klamath Basin|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=U89OpWh0itoC|location= |publisher= University of California Press|page= 167|isbn=0520213149}}</ref> [[Obsidian]] [[arrowhead]]s are frequent finds, whose varieties include Northern Sided Notched, [[Elko point|Elko type corner notched]], and Gunther type points.<ref>Justice, N. D. (2002). [https://books.google.com/books?id=kzrfXiifiToC Stone Age spear and arrow points of California and the Great Basin] Indiana University Press. Page 174</ref> \n\nExcavations and sampling started in 1966 by Klamath educator Carrol Howe. The site was described by Garth Sampson in a 1985 publication of the [[University of Oregon]], located in [[Eugene, Oregon]].<ref name=\"geoarch\">{{cite journal|last=Sampson|first=C. Garth|title=Nightfire Island: Later holocene lakemarsh adaptation on the western edge of the great basin|journal=Geoarcheology|year=1985|volume=2|pages=247|url=https://escholarship.org/content/qt5wq3p6dd/qt5wq3p6dd.pdf|accessdate=April 5, 2020|doi=}}</ref> \n\n==History==\nHuman occupation of the Klamath Basin areas may have begun around 6000 BCE.<ref name=\"geoarch\" /> Settlement by [[Modoc people]] on the banks of Sheepy Creek is likely to have begun approximately 4000 years [[Common Era|BCE]],<ref name=\"grayson\" /> shortly after the eruption of [[Mount Mazama]], as evidenced by a layer of volcanic ash on the lake bed just below the layer that marks the appearance of a new village.<ref name=howe /> \n\nThe shallow water level of the marsh, the clay loam, and the basalt rubble basin extended all around and over this area afforded only a weak foundation for settlement. To compensate, inhabitants carried in rocks to strengthen the village's foundation. After centuries of this procedure, they had built an island of an area approximately {{Convert|2.5|acre||abbr=}}. \n\nSurrounded by marshlands, the villagers could fish and hunt [[Anseriformes|waterfowl]].<ref>Kittredge, W. (2000). [https://books.google.com/books?id=U89OpWh0itoC Balancing water: restoring the Klamath Basin]. Univ of California Press. Page 176</ref> The springs nearest to Nightfire Island are geothermal waters, adding to the comfort of the villagers. During the dry months, the receding water levels allowed for the establishment of a secure hunting station. Charcoal remains show evidence of cooking pits and cremated burial sites within the island. Bones show an early abundance of duck with additional diversity appearing in later years.<ref name=\"geoarch\" />\n \nWaterfowl droppings within layers of the excavation site show that there were times where the site was abandoned for several hundred years, probably because of the rising of the levels of Indian Tom Lake, climate change during the hot and dry middle [[Holocene]], or changes in the Keno fault.<ref name=\"grayson\">Grayson, D. K. (1976). A note on the prehistoric avifauna of the Lower Klamath Basin. The Auk, 93(4), 830-833.</ref> When water levels receded, occupation resumed with the appearance of black charcoal levels from cooking and cremation fires.<ref name=\"howe\" />\n\n==Archeology==\nExcavations of archeological site 4-SK-4 have produced large collections of bird, mammal, and fish bones, large amounts of obsidian technology (particularly Elko points), bone artifacts, mortars and other stone artifacts as well as other cultural detritus.<ref name=\"grayson\" /><ref name=\"Murguia\" /> These occupational debris reach a maximum of 3 meters deep. The lower stratum is [[Lake|lacustrine]], waterway [[diatom]]-rich silt from the original lake floor present during the first occupation of the site. From there, the strata consist of a series of [[silt]], streamland and [[loam]] forming a [[duripan]] horizon.<ref>{{cite web|title=Modoc Series|url=https://soilseries.sc.egov.usda.gov/OSD_Docs/M/MODOC.html|accessdate=April 14, 2020 |author=USDA Soil Series Descriptions and Series Classification|date=August, 2004}}</ref>\n\nVillagers cooked small animals by boiling them in baskets, while larger animals were cooked in rock roasting ovens primarily composed of large basalt rocks. Along with oven rocks, other rocks included broken fragments of [[mortar and pestle]]s and banded stones used for weights. Banded rocks are generally used for outdoor support such as tying down canoes.<ref>{{cite book |last= Carlisle|first= Rodney P. |author-link= |date= 2007|title= Native America from Prehistory to First Contact|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=J7FZggSz3eAC|location= |publisher= ABC-CLIO|page= 177|isbn=1851098291}}</ref> On Nightfire Island, banded rocks may have been used for indoor weights since they were found inside the houses and in roasting pits.<ref>Howe, p. 64</ref> The number of these rocks and their weight exceeds the traditional canoe weights and even the weights used by the [[Modoc people]] for the balsa-type rafts. The banded rocks from Nightfire Island show signs of burning mixed with charcoal from cooking fires.<ref>Howe, p. 67</ref> Some stones were used for boiling food in basketry by placing the hot basalt or lava stones into tightly packed woven water-filled baskets.<ref>{{cite book |last= The Library of Native Americans|first= |author-link= |date= 2003|title= The Modoc of California and Oregon|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=6AjymTpzRTUC|location= |publisher= The [[Rosen Publishing]] Group|page= 19|isbn=1404226605}}</ref>\n\nThe presence of buffalo hide on Nightfire Island suggest the village hunters used obsidian and [[spear-thrower]]s. The most common arrow point found on the site is the [[Cascade point|Cascade-type]]. Additionally, the excavation has produced several [[Lithic reduction|pressure-flaking]] tools made of bone and antler used for projectiles, especially before the bow and arrow were in use.<ref name=\"Howe72\">Howe, p. 72</ref> Stone anvils from the excavation had single and bilateral worn out pits used for [[knapping]] the obsidian to break the [[spall]]s from the rock.<ref>{{cite book |last= Hranicky|first= Wm Jack |author-link= |date= 2013|title= Archaeological Concepts, Techniques, and Terminology for American Prehistoric Lithic Technology|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=PSDtkmsHIEsC|location= |publisher= AuthorHouse|page=82, 277 |isbn=1481751743}}</ref> The large amount of anvils found on Nightfire Island suggest they were used for other purposes than knapping, including cracking bones. The side pits are not worn out consistent with the use as a maul or for pounding food.<ref name=\"Howe72\" /> \n\nWhile Modocs of the [[Great Basin]] had chipped-stone crescents or lunates,<ref>{{cite book |last= Justice|first= Noel D. |date= 2002|title= Stone Age Spear and Arrow Points of California and the Great Basin|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=kzrfXiifiToC|location= |publisher= Indiana University Press|page=116|isbn=0253108837}}</ref><ref>University of California Archaeological Survey, & Berkeley. Archaeological Research Facility. (1960). [https://books.google.com/books?id=0rKVdi0HrusC Reports of the University of California Archaeological Survey]. University of California Archaeological Survey, Department of Anthropology, University of California. p. 44.</ref> their presence has not been confirmed on Nightfire Island. Some smaller versions have been excavated but they are of a different shape and material.<ref name=\"Howe33\">Howe, p. 33 </ref> An increase in small, stemmed and cornr notched arrowheads have been discovered on layers of approximately 2,500 years BCE which corresponds to the peak in the dabbling duck remains and the adoption of the bow and arrow. \n\n===Culture===\nExcavations have unearthed structures that suggest buildings similar to [[sweat lodge]]s on Nightfire Island. Carbon-14 dated to approximately 1,500 years ago, these would be the oldest remains of a sweat lodge.<ref name=\"Murguia\" />\n\nA higher than usual frequency of neuronal malformations in remains discovered within Nightfire Island suggest tentatively that [[inbreeding]] might have occurred.<ref>Bennett, K. A. (1972). [https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/ajpa.1330360315 Lumbo\u2010sacral malformations and spina bifida occulta in a group of proto\u2010historic Modoc Indians]. ''American Journal of Physical Anthropology'', 36(3), 435-439.</ref> Studies of skeletal remains also revealed an unusually large and deep fossae lateral in the 1st and 2nd sacral tuberosities, suggesting a very strong postural ligament attachment.<ref>de la Mata, R. C., & Bonavia, D. (1980). [https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1086/202506?journalCode=ca Lumbosacral malformations and spina bifida in a Peruvian preceramic child]. ''Current Anthropology'', 21(4), 515-516.</ref>\n\nNightfire Modocs were prominent waterfowl hunters. While rainfall was not consistent, the alkali open marshes held in place by block-fault ridges provided a rich habitat for local and migratory waterfowl. In the Fall [[Northern pintail|pintails]] and [[mallard]]s arrived first along the [[Pacific Flyway]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Northern Pintail |url=http://www.seattleaudubon.org/birdweb/bird/northern_pintail|accessdate=April 14, 2020 |author=Seattle Audubon Society|date=February 2, 2009 |}}</ref> and later in the season [[American wigeon|baldpates]] and [[canvasback]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=American Wigeon|url=http://www.ducks.org/hunting/waterfowl-id/american-wigeon|accessdate=April 14, 2020 |author=Ducks Unlimited|date=|}}</ref> [[Coot]] and the [[common merganser]] were common as overwinter birds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Common mergansers: The piscivorous divers|url=https://www.heraldandnews.com/outdoors/common-mergansers-the-piscivorous-divers/article_56d9b09e-b057-50e1-bb86-efde38509c97.html|accessdate=April 14, 2020 |author=Gary Vequist (Herald and News|date=21 Dec 2018}}</ref> On the northern direction, white [[Snow goose|snow geese]] arrived first and white [[Greater white-fronted goose|fronted geese]] were among the latest to fly by. Nightfire Island soils didn't contain egg shells,<ref> Howe, p. 36-37</ref> however residents took advantage of bird-nesting season for the stability of their life cycle.\n\n===Paleontology finds===\nAnalysis of samples from Nightfire Island show that residents ate a great variety of birds: ''[[Podiceps]]'' spp., ''[[Cygnus (genus)|Cygnus]]'' spp., ''[[Branta]]'' spp., ''[[Anas]]'' spp., ''[[Aythya]]'' spp., ''[[Bucephala (bird)|Bucephala]]'' spp., and ''[[Mergus]]'' spp.<ref>Howe, p. 40</ref> Additionally, bones of eagles, owls and raven were also found among the kitchen [[midden]].<ref name=\"grayson\" /> Deeper levels of the marshy lake allowed for a higher quantity of waterfowl during the [[Common Era|CE]].\n\nThe bird life of Nightfire Island includes the following species dated by [[Radiocarbon dating|radiocarbon]] determinations:<ref name=\"grayson\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Dates and species defined by number of identified specimens\n|-\n!from 4000-3000 BC\n!from 3000-2200 BC\n!from 2020 BC-AD 0\n!from 0-1400 AD\n|-\n|[[Common loon]] (0)\n|[[Common loon]] (0)\n|[[Common loon]] (5)\n|[[Common loon]] (17)\n|-\n|[[Horned grebe]] (0)\n|[[Horned grebe]] (1)\n|[[Horned grebe]] (5)\n|[[Horned grebe]] (25)\n|-\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (1)\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (5)\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (15)\n|[[Black-necked grebe]] (10)\n|-\n|[[Western grebe]] (1)\n|[[Western grebe]] (2)\n|[[Western grebe]] (28)\n|[[Western grebe]] (280)\n|-\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (5)\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (9)\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (27)\n|[[Pied-billed grebe]] (51)\n|-\n|[[American white pelican]] (0)\n|[[American white pelican]] (1)\n|[[American white pelican]] (4)\n|[[American white pelican]] (0)\n|-\n|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (1)\n|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (0)\n|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (0)\n|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (6)\n|-\n|[[Great blue heron]] (1)\n|[[Great blue heron]] (0)\n|[[Great blue heron]] (0)\n|[[Great blue heron]] (4)\n|-\n|[[Black-crowned night heron]] (0)\n|[[Black-crowned night heron]] (1)\n|[[Black-crowned night heron]] (3)\n|[[Black-crowned night heron]] (2)\n|-\n|[[American bittern]] (1)\n|[[American bittern]] (1)\n|[[American bittern]] (1)\n|[[American bittern]] (1)\n|-\n|[[Tundra swan]] (1)\n|[[Tundra swan]] (6)\n|[[Tundra swan]] (1)\n|[[Tundra swan]] (6)\n|-\n|[[Trumpeter swan]] (1)\n|[[Trumpeter swan]] (0)\n|[[Trumpeter swan]] (2)\n|[[Trumpeter swan]] (1)\n|-\n|[[Canada goose]] (2)\n|[[Canada goose]] (4)\n|[[Canada goose]] (16)\n|[[Canada goose]] (6)\n|-\n|[[Mallard|Mallard duck]] (3)\n|[[Mallard|Mallard duck]] (45)\n|[[Mallard|Mallard duck]] (95)\n|[[Mallard|Mallard duck]] (52)\n|-\n|[[Gadwall]], [[Northern pintail|pintails]],<br> [[American wigeon]],<br> and/or [[Northern shoveler|shovelers]] (3)\n|[[Gadwall]], [[Northern pintail|pintails]],<br> [[American wigeon]],<br> and/or [[Northern shoveler|shovelers]] (19)\n|[[Gadwall]], [[Northern pintail|pintails]],<br> [[American wigeon]],<br> and/or [[Northern shoveler|shovelers]] (41)\n||[[Gadwall]], [[Northern pintail|pintails]],<br> [[American wigeon]],<br> and/or [[Northern shoveler|shovelers]] (51)\n|-\n|[[Green-winged teal]], [[Blue-winged teal|Blue-winged]]<br> [[Blue-winged teal|teal]] and/or  [[Cinnamon teal]] (1)\n|[[Green-winged teal]], [[Blue-winged teal|Blue-winged]]<br> [[Blue-winged teal|teal]] and/or  [[Cinnamon teal]] (2)\n||[[Green-winged teal]], [[Blue-winged teal|Blue-winged]]<br> [[Blue-winged teal|teal]] and/or  [[Cinnamon teal]] (36)\n|[[Green-winged teal]], [[Blue-winged teal|Blue-winged]]<br> [[Blue-winged teal|teal]] and/or  [[Cinnamon teal]] (14)\n|-\n|[[Ring-necked duck]] (0)\n|[[Ring-necked duck]] (0)\n|[[Ring-necked duck]] (1)\n|[[Ring-necked duck]] (112)\n|-\n|[[Canvasback]] (0)\n|[[Canvasback]] (2)\n|[[Canvasback]] (15)\n|[[Canvasback]] (131)\n|-\n|[[Greater scaup]], [[Redhead (bird)|Redhead duck]],</br> and/or [[Lesser scaup]] (4)\n|[[Greater scaup]], [[Redhead (bird)|Redhead duck]],</br> and/or [[Lesser scaup]] (7)\n|[[Greater scaup]], [[Redhead (bird)|Redhead duck]],</br> and/or [[Lesser scaup]] (12)\n|[[Greater scaup]], [[Redhead (bird)|Redhead duck]],</br> and/or [[Lesser scaup]] (3)\n|-\n|[[Common goldeneye]] (0)\n|[[Common goldeneye]] (0)\n|[[Common goldeneye]] (2)\n|[[Common goldeneye]] (0)\n|- \n|[[Bufflehead]] (3)\n|[[Bufflehead]] (3)\n|[[Bufflehead]] (13)\n|[[Bufflehead]] (25)\n|-\n|[[Ruddy duck]] (17)\n|[[Ruddy duck]] (9)\n|[[Ruddy duck]] (48)\n|[[Ruddy duck]] (92)\n|-\n|[[Hooded merganser]] (0)\n|[[Hooded merganser]] (0)\n|[[Hooded merganser]] (3)\n|[[Hooded merganser]] (103)\n|-\n