       = 6:34\n}}\n\n'''UK cassette single'''<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=Doesn't Really Matter|others=Janet Jackson|year=2000|type=booklet|publisher=Def Jam Records|id=562 916-4|location=Europe}}</ref>\n{{Track listing |title_width=30em\n| title1        = Doesn't Really Matter (Radio Edit)\n| length1       = 4:18\n| title2        = Doesn't Really Matter (Album Version)\n| length2       = 4:55\n}}\n\n'''UK maxi single'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Doesnt-Really-Matter-Janet-Jackson/dp/B00004XP5U|title=Doesn't Really Matter - Maxi-Single, CD Single|publisher=Amazon|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n{{Track listing |title_width=30em\n| title1        = Doesn't Really Matter (Radio Edit)\n| length1       = 4:18\n| title2        = Doesn't Really Matter (Rockwilder Mix)\n| length2       = 5:41\n| title3        = Doesn't Really Matter (Jonathan Peters Club Mix)\n| length3       = 8:49\n| title4        = Doesn't Really Matter (Video)\n}}\n\n{{col-2}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2000)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Australia|28|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2011|refname=\"AU\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|28|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2011}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia|13|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2011|refname=\"Wallonia\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canadatopsingles|2|chartid=7094|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 19, 2019|refname=\"can\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canadaadultcontemporary|49|chartid=7182|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 19, 2019}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Canada Dance/Urban (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Canada's Official National Dance Top 40|magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|volume=71|issue=23|page=2|date=October 9, 2000|accessdate=September 19, 2019|url=http://rpmimages.3345.ca/pdfs/Volume%2071-No.%2023-October%209%202000.pdf}}</ref>\n|14\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|Denmark ([[IFPI Danmark|IFPI]])<ref name=\"Denmark\">{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/00s/2000/MM-2000-09-02.pdf|title=Top National Sellers Week 36/00|magazine=Music & Media|volume=17|number=36|page=13|date=September 2, 2000|accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref>\n| 9\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|[[European Hot 100 Singles]] (''[[Music & Media]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/00s/2000/MM-2000-08-26.pdf |title=Eurochart Hot 100 Singles Week 35/00|accessdate=April 26, 2019|magazine=[[Music & Media]]|volume=17|issue=35|page=7}}</ref>\n| 15\n|-\n{{single chart|France|40|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2011}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|23|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|songid=4397|rowheader=true|accessdate=October 17, 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Ireland2|21|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 19, 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Italy|10|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2011|refname=\"Italy\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch40|11|year=2000|week=34|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 12, 2020|refname=\"Dutch40\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|15|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 26, 2018|refname=\"Dutch100\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|New Zealand|27|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2011|refname=\"NZ\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Norway|13|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2011|refname=\"Norway\"}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Poland ([[Polish Society of the Phonographic Industry|ZPAV]])<ref name=\"Poland\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/UK/Music-and-Media/00s/2000/MM-2000-09-30.pdf|title=Major Market Airplay|magazine=Music & Media|volume=17|issue=40|page=23|date=September 30, 2000|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| 2\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|13|date=20000813|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Spain|9|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 10, 2018|refname=\"Spain\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Sweden|14|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2011|refname=\"Sweden\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Switzerland|17|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2011|refname=\"Switzerland\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UK|5|date=20000813|rowheader=true|accessdate=July 20, 2012}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKrandb|2|date=20000813|rowheader=true|refname=\"UKR&B\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|1|artist=Janet Jackson|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 5, 2011}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardrandbhiphop|3|artist=Janet Jackson|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 5, 2011|refname=\"USR&B\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardpopsongs|3|artist=Janet Jackson|rowheader=true|accessdate=July 2, 2014|refname=\"Top40\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardrhythmic|2|artist=Janet Jackson|rowheader=true|accessdate=July 2, 2014|refname=\"Rhythmic\"}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2000)\n! scope=\"col\"| Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Belgium (Ultratop 50 Wallonia)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/fr/annual.asp?year=2000|title=Rapports annuels 2000|publisher=[[Ultratop]]|language=French|accessdate=September 19, 2019}}</ref>\n| 63\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Netherlands (Dutch Top 40)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.top40.nl/bijzondere-lijsten/top-100-jaaroverzichten/2000|title=Top 100-Jaaroverzicht van 2000|publisher=[[Dutch Top 40]]|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| 78\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Netherlands (Single Top 100)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=2000&cat=s|title=Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 2000|publisher=[[Dutch Charts|MegaCharts]]|language=Dutch|accessdate=September 19, 2019}}</ref>\n| 91\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/00s/2000/BB-2000-12-30.pdf|title=The Year in Music 2000; Hot 100 Spotlights|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|page=YE-46|date=December 30, 2000|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| 18\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US Mainstream Top 40 (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Most Played Mainstream Top 40 Songs of 2000|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/Billboard-Airplay/2000/BBAM-2000-12-22.pdf|page=54|date=December 22, 2000|magazine=[[Billboard Radio Monitor]]|issn=1556-7338|format=PDF|volume=8|issue=51|accessdate=April 12, 2020}} </ref>\n| 31\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2000/hot-r-and-and-b-hip-hop-songs|title=Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs \u2013 Year-End 2000|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| 29\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US Rhythmic (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Most Played Rhythmic Top 40 Songs of 2000|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/Billboard-Airplay/2000/BBAM-2000-12-22.pdf|page=56|date=December 22, 2000|magazine=[[Billboard Radio Monitor]]|issn=1556-7338|format=PDF|volume=8|issue=51|accessdate=April 12, 2020}} </ref>\n| 18\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|artist=Janet Jackson|title=Doesn't Really Matter|relyear=2000|certyear=2000|award=Silver |accessdate=June 5, 2015|refname=\"UKCert\"}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=single|artist=Janet Jackson|title=Doesn't Really Matter|relyear=2000|certyear=2000|award=Gold|refname=\"RIAA\"|accessdate=June 5, 2015|salesamount=600,000|salesref=<ref name=\"Sales\">{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ghMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA64|title=Best-Selling Records of 2000|magazine=Billboard|date=February 10, 2001|accessdate=June 5, 2015|page=64|issn=0006-2510|volume=113|number=6}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Region\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| United States\n| May 23, 2000\n| [[Contemporary hit radio]]\n| {{hlist|[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]|[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]}}\n| <ref name=\"BillboardRelease\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| United Kingdom\n| August 7, 2000\n| rowspan=\"2\"| {{hlist|[[CD single]]|[[cassette single]]}}\n| {{hlist|Def Jam|[[Mercury Records|Mercury]]}}\n| <ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/janet-jackson-66-1396324|title=Jackson Case Thrown Out|website=[[NME]]|date=July 25, 2000|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| United States\n| rowspan=\"2\"| August 8, 2000\n| {{hlist|Def Jam|Virgin}}\n| <ref name=\"CD\"/></br><ref name=\"Cassette\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|United Kingdom\n|[[Twelve-inch single|12-inch single]]\n| {{hlist|Def Jam|Mercury}}\n| <ref name=\"UKVinyl\"/>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Janet Jackson singles}}\n\n[[Category:2000 singles]]\n[[Category:2000 songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings singles]]\n[[Category:Electropop songs]]\n[[Category:Janet Jackson songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Joseph Kahn]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Janet Jackson]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]\n[[Category:Songs written for films]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|2000 single by Janet Jackson}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Doesn't Really Matter\n| cover      = Janet Jackson - Doesn't Really Matter.png\n| alt        = Jackson is seen hugging Eddie Murphy's character, Sherman Klump, while surrounded by the Klump family. The text above reads Janet Jackson \u2013 Doesn't Really Matter\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Janet Jackson]]\n| album      = [[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps (soundtrack)|Nutty Professor II: The Klumps Soundtrack]] ''and'' [[All for You (Janet Jackson album)|All for You]]\n| released   = {{start date|2000|5|23|mf=y}}\n| format     = \n*[[Twelve-inch single|12-inch single]]\n*[[cassette single]]\n*[[CD single]]\n*[[maxi single]]\n| recorded   = \n| studio     = Flyte Tyme, [[Edina, Minnesota]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      = \n*[[Electropop]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n*[[Dance music|dance]]\n<!--Do not add unsourced genres-->\n| length     = 4:18\n| label      = \n*[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n*[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n| writer     = \n*Janet Jackson\n*James Harris III\n*Terry Lewis\n| producer   = \n*[[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]\n*Janet Jackson\n| prev_title = [[Girlfriend/Boyfriend]]\n| prev_year  = 1999\n| next_title = [[All for You (Janet Jackson song)|All for You]]\n| next_year  = 2001\n}}\n\n\"'''Doesn't Really Matter'''\" is a song by American singer [[Janet Jackson]] from the [[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the 2000 film ''[[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps]]'', and her seventh studio album ''[[All for You (Janet Jackson album)|All for You]]'' (2001). It was written and produced by Jackson, [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]. The track was sent to [[contemporary hit radio]] in the US on May 23, 2000, after an [[Mastering (audio)|unmastered]] version was leaked to several radio stations. It is an upbeat [[electropop]], [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[Dance music|dance]] song with a syncopated drum loop and [[bassline]]. Based on a previously discarded poem Jackson wrote, the lyrics are about her film character's love for [[The Nutty Professor (character)|The Nutty Professor]].\n\nThe track received generally positive reviews from music critics, who praised its upbeat sound and Jackson's [[breathy voice]]. \"Doesn't Really Matter\" topped the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] for three consecutive weeks, becoming the singer's ninth US chart-topper. It was Jackson's 19th single to be certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), making her only the third singer, after [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Whitney Houston]], to achieve this feat. The song peaked at number five on the [[UK Singles Chart]], becoming Jackson's 15th single to reach the top 10 in the UK. It also peaked within the top 10 in Canada, Denmark, Poland, Italy, and Spain.\n\nThe [[Joseph Kahn]]-directed music video resembles an [[abstract art|abstract]], futuristic environment based on Japanese culture. It features an [[AIBO]], a prototype of the [[Acura CL]]-X, morphing clothes, and a dance sequence on a tilting platform. Production of the video costed over $2.5 million (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|2.5|2000|r=1}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}), making it one of the [[list of most expensive music videos|most expensive music videos of all time]]. To promote the single, Jackson performed it on British television program ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' and at the [[2000 MTV Video Music Awards]]. The song was also performed during four of the singer's concert tours, and her 2019 Las Vegas residency, [[Janet Jackson: Metamorphosis]].\n\n==Background and development==\n\"Doesn't Really Matter\" was written and produced by [[Janet Jackson]], [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]] as the theme for the [[Universal Pictures]] film ''[[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps]]'', starring Jackson and actor [[Eddie Murphy]].<ref name=\"LinerNotes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=Doesn't Really Matter|others=[[Janet Jackson]]|year=2000|type=booklet|publisher=[[Def Jam Records]]|id=562 916-2|location=New York City}}</ref> When asked to contribute a single for the [[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps (soundtrack)|movie's soundtrack]], Jackson stated that she would consider if she found an appropriate song.<ref name=\"Bronson\">{{cite book|last=Bronson|first=Fred|year=2003|title=Billboard's Hottest Hot 100 Hits|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard Books]]|edition=3|page=902|isbn=0823077381}}</ref> The single would allow Jackson to continue releasing music, while simultaneously devoting time to her film career.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Action Jackson|magazine=[[USA Weekend]]|date=July 21\u201323, 2000|page=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T9cDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA181#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Janet at the Crossroads|last=Norment|first=Lynn|magazine=[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]|volume=41|number=1|page=181|date=November 2000|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> To help inspire Jackson, director [[Peter Segal]] brought a rough cut of the film to Flyte Tyme Studios where the singer was recording her seventh album, ''[[All for You (Janet Jackson album)|All for You]]''. She decided to write an uptempo love song rather than a [[Sentimental ballad|ballad]], inspired by Segal finding her love for Murphy's unattractive character in the film convincing.<ref name=\"Bronson\"/>\n\nThe lyrics of \"Doesn't Really Matter\" were based on a poem Jackson found which she previously wrote and disposed of.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2015/jun/03/janet-jackson-10-of-the-best|title=Janet Jackson: 10 of the best|last=Cragg|first=Michael|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=June 3, 2015|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> The poem's lyrics were kept intact, although its structure was altered. Jackson wrote further lyrics for the song during the same night Jam came up with the melody alongside drum programmer Alex Richburg.<ref name=\"Bronson\"/> After an early version of the song was created, Jackson requested Jam and Richburg to add more instrumentation, however Jam decided to record from [[Broadcasting#Recorded and live forms|live to tape]] after Richburg left the studio.<ref name=\"Keyboard\">{{cite magazine|last=Rule|first=Greg|date=November 2000|title=Jimmy Jam: Inside Flyte Tyme studios|magazine=[[Keyboard (magazine)|Keyboard]]|volume=26|issue=11|pages=32-40|issn=07300158}}</ref> Initially conceived as a \"slow melody\", Jam chose to increase its [[tempo]].<ref name=\"Bronson\" />\n\nTwo different choruses were written by Jam and Jackson; Jam wrote \"Nutty, nutty, nutty, my love for you\" while Jackson wrote \"Doesn't really matter\". They decided to use Jackson's chorus, and include Jam's chorus towards the end of the track. Jackson presented three songs to Segal on May 12, 2000, three days prior to his set deadline for the soundtrack. He chose \"Doesn't Really Matter\", believing it was a better fit and a \"summertime record\". A slightly modified version was included on ''All for You'', featuring an alternate introduction and elements from the song's [[Rockwilder]] remix.<ref name=\"Bronson\" />\n\n==Composition==\n{{listen|pos=right|filename=Janet - Doesn't Really Matter.ogg|title=\"Doesn't Really Matter\"||format=[[Ogg]]|description=The chorus is played at nearly twice the speed as the start-stop verses.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Most of the song was played live to tape, while a small portion was sequenced to double the melody.<ref name=\"Keyboard\"/>}}\n\"Doesn't Really Matter\" is an [[electropop]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/vault/7897104/nsync-matchbox-twenty-2000-summer-songs|title='N Sync, Matchbox Twenty, and More\u2014Tracks That Take You Back To Summer of 2000|author=Billboad Staff|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=August 23, 2017|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]],<ref name=\"Guardian\"/><ref name=\"Farber\">{{cite newspaper|last=Farber|first=Jim|date=18 July 2000|title='Nutty Professor' Music Mixed Bag; Freddie King|newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]|page=43}}</ref> and [[Dance music|dance]] song.<ref name=\"BillboardTop100\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/9339652/best-songs-of-2000-top-100|title=The 100 Greatest Songs of 2000: Staff Picks|last=Daniel|first=Danica|website=Billboard|date=March 23, 2020|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Although making using of [[Funk music|funk]] production, common in R&B music at the time of its 2000 release, the track was viewed as an R&B-pop take on [[lounge music]].<ref name=\"Farber\"/> Its upbeat pop sound is akin to Jackson's 1995 single \"[[Runaway (Janet Jackson song)|Runaway]]\", a stark contrast to the sparse R&B of her previous album, ''[[The Velvet Rope]]''.<ref name=\"ChuckBillboard\">{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mg8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA31|title=Reviews and Previews|magazine=Billboard|last=Taylor|first=Chuck|authorlink=Chuck Taylor (music journalist)|volume=112|number=24|page=31|date=June 10, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Music critic Jim Farber compared the retro-style melody in \"Doesn't Really Matter\" to compositions by [[Burt Bacharach]].<ref name=\"Farber\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20267962,00.html|title=Now That's What I Call Music! 5|last=Farber|first=Jim|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=November 17, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> The production makes use of sparse, programmed percussion.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Trammell|first=Matthew|date=20 November 2017|title=Current State|magazine=[[The New Yorker]]|volume=93|issue=37|page=20|issn=0028792X}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/janet-jackson-all-for-you/94|title=Janet Jackson: All for You \u2013 Music Review|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|date=June 13, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe majority of the track was played live to tape, even though it sounded [[Music sequencer|sequenced]]. Jam recalled that only a small portion was sequenced, which was used to double the [[melody]].<ref name=\"Keyboard\"/> The song utilizes both a syncopated drum loop and a [[bassline]], which passes the [[circle of fifths]] to reach the [[Circle of fifths#Modulation and chord progression|V chord]]. The bassline allows space for the [[snare drum]] to be heard on the second and fourth beats, as well as accentuating the snare before the fourth beat is played.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Flavor of the month: Janet's 'Doesn't Really Matter'|magazine=[[Bass Player (magazine)|Bass Player]]|date=November 2000|volume=11|issue=11|page=94|issn=1050785X}}</ref>\n\nThe song begins with a 20-second mid-tempo introduction performed by Jackson in [[breathy voice]].<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Jackson performs a [[falsetto]] [[Trill (music)|trill]] on the lyrics \"My love / For you / Is unconditional too\".<ref name=\"EWFlashback\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1226514,00.html|title=Chart Flashback|website=Entertainment Weekly|last=Pastorek|first=Whitney|date=August 15, 2006|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> The chorus has nearly twice the speed of the stop-start verses. A more fluid [[Break (music)|breakdown]] features halfway, offsetting the pace and high-energy dynamic of the chorus.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> The song also utilizes a [[Modulation (music)|key change]].<ref name=\"Dotmusic\"/> According to Jackson, the lyrics for \"Doesn't Really Matter\" are about her film character's love for [[The Nutty Professor (character)|The Nutty Professor]] and refers to \"how it doesn't matter what is on the exterior, but the interior\".<ref name=\"Making\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\"Doesn't Really Matter\" received generally positive reviews from music critics. [[Chuck Eddy]] of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' regarded it as Jackson's best single since 1990's \"[[Black Cat (song)|Black Cat]]\", stating that \"the melody's subliminal Asianness makes the nothingness of her piddly voice pretty\u2014fragile like [[rice paper]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2001/03/13/backstabs-in-the-material-world/|title=Backstabs in the Material World|website=[[The Village Voice]]|last=Eddy|first=Chuck|date=March 13, 2001|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref> In the ''[[New York Daily News]]'', Jim Farber viewed the track as innovative, noting that it \"dodges current clich\u00e9s\" and has \"the yearning freshness of a summer breeze\". According to him, \"the baby's-breath tune and lightly skittish beat provide the perfect accompaniment for Jackson's coo of a voice\".<ref name=\"Farber\"/> Carol Cooper of ''Sonicnet'' wrote that Jackson's vocals \"deserve special mention for the deft way she speed-sings verses and choruses so as to accent their underlying rhythmic patterns\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonicnet.com/reviews/rev.jhtml?genreNameForDisplay=Pop&genreDirectoryName=pop&cid=1443078&configPathName=Pop|title=The Princess Of Pop Returns|last=Cooper|first=Carol|website=Sonicnet|date=June 17, 2001|access-date=April 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010617175735/http://www.sonicnet.com/reviews/rev.jhtml?genreNameForDisplay=Pop&genreDirectoryName=pop&cid=1443078&configPathName=Pop|archive-date=June 17, 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref>  \n\nIn his review of the single for [[AllMusic]], [[Promis (musician)|Jose F. Promis]] called it \"impossibly catchy\".<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/doesnt-really-matter-us-cd5-cassette-mw0000101400|title=Doesn't Really Matter [US CD5/Cassette]|work=[[AllMusic]]|last=Promis|first=Jose F.|authorlink=Promis (musician)|date=August 8, 2000|access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Melissa Marschheuser of the ''[[The Orlando Sentinel]]'' wrote that the song has \"a beat you just can't help but hum along to\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2000-08-04/entertainment/0008030478_1_nutty-professor-ii-buddy-love-klump|title=The Nutty Professor II: The Klumps|website=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|last=Marschheuser|first=Melissa|date=August 4, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Matt Diehl of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' viewed the track as \"effervescent\", and cited it and [[R. Kelly]]'s \"Just a Touch\" as the only two consequential R&B songs on the soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,64793,00.html|title=Nutty Professor II: The Klumps Soundtrack Review|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Diehl|first=Matt|date=July 10, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> In his review of ''All for You'' for ''Entertainment Weekly'', Tom Sinclair regarded the song as \"competent hack pop\".<ref name=\"Sinclair\">{{cite website|url=https://ew.com/article/2001/04/30/all-you-2/|title=All for You|website=Entertainment Weekly|last=Sinclair|first=Tom|date=May 4, 2001|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Sean Piccoli of the ''[[Sun-Sentinel]]'' believed it had  \"a less suffocating shade of pop\" than other tracks on ''All for You''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2001-05-01/lifestyle/0104300241_1_janet-jackson-album-jackson-family-song|title=Janet Jackson Says Goodbye With A Bite|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|last=Piccoli|first=Sean|date=May 1, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[Neumu]]''{{'}}s Anthony Carew found the song \"surgically clean\" and the production \"suitably slick\", noting that Jam and Lewis were \"so self-conscious of their skills they cut-in the word 'edit' as a cute cut-up gimmick\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neumu.net/fortyfour/2001/2001-00105/2001-00105_fortyfour.shtml|title=Janet Jackson - All for You|last=Carew|first=Anthony|website=[[Neumu]]|date=May 1, 2001|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> [[Chuck Taylor (music journalist)|Chuck Taylor]] of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' called the song \"frothy\" and \"a leftover from another time\", but argued that it was \"innocent fun\" and \"a smile-bearing throwback\" that highlighted Jackson's \"still-youthful vocal musings\".<ref name=\"ChuckBillboard\"/> ''[[Dotmusic]]''{{'}}s Gary Crossing was more critical, calling it a \"disappointing fare\" with a \"bland\" vocal mix, writing that \"apart from the key changes there's barely anything of interest here\".<ref name=\"Dotmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dotmusic.com/artists/JanetJackson/reviews/August2000/reviews14938.asp|title=Janet Jackson - 'Doesn't Really Matter' (Def Jam)|last=Crossing|first=Gary|website=[[Dotmusic]]|date=August 10, 2000|access-date=April 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010610160844/http://www.dotmusic.com/artists/JanetJackson/reviews/August2000/reviews14938.asp|archive-date=June 10, 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Billboard'' included \"Doesn't Really Matter\" in its list of The Greatest Songs of 2000 at number 78.<ref name=\"BillboardTop100\"/> ''[[The Guardian]]'' placed it at number eight in its 2015 list of Jackson's best songs.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"Doesn't Really Matter\" received early attention a week ahead of its US radio release on May 23, 2000, after an [[Mastering (audio)|unmastered]] version [[Internet leak|leaked]] to several radio stations, some of who made their own [[radio edit]] from the leak.<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/971570/jimmy-jam-prepping-klumps-soundtrack.jhtml|title=Producer Jimmy Jam Readying 'Klumps' Soundtrack, Janet Jackson Album|last=Schumacher-Rasmussen|first=Eric|website=[[MTV News]]|date=June 3, 2000|access-date=February 2, 2001}}</ref><ref name=\"BillboardRelease>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mQ8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA33#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Janet Jackson Single First 'Nutty' Release; Soundtrack To Sequel Via Def Jam/Def Soul|last=Mitchell|first=Gail|magazine=Billboard|volume=112|number=23|page=33|date=June 3, 2000|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> It became the most added song on pop, rhythmic, and urban radio formats upon release.<ref name=\"RandR\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/2000s/2000/RR-2000-06-23.pdf|title=Janet And Friends|magazine=[[Radio & Records]]|number=1356|page=1|date=June 23, 2000|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> On the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] issue dated June 17, 2000, \"Doesn't Really Matter\" debuted at number 59 on airplay alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2000-06-17?rank=59|title=The Hot 100 \u2013 Week of June 17, 2000|website=Billboard|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Following its [[CD single|CD]] and [[cassette single]] release on August 8, 2000, \"Doesn't Really Matter\" climbed to number one, selling 96,000 copies during its first full week of sales.<ref name=\"CD\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Doesnt-Really-Matter-Janet-Jackson/dp/B00004WFAC/ref=tmm_acd_title_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=&sr=|title=Doesn't Really Matter - Audio CD|publisher=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Cassette\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Doesnt-Really-Matter-Janet-Jackson/dp/B00004WFAD/ref=tmm_acs_title_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=&sr=|title=Doesn't Really Matter - Audio Cassette|publisher=Amazon|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spotlight\">{{cite magazine|last=Pietroluongo|first=Silvio|date=August 26, 2000|title=Hot 100 Spotlight|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZhAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA101&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false|magazine=Billboard|volume=112|number=35|page=101|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> The song spent three consecutive weeks at number one before being replaced by \"[[Music (Madonna song)|Music]]\" by [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]. It was Jackson's ninth US number-one single and made her the first singer to achieve a number one in the 1980s, 1990s, and 2000s in the US.<ref name=\"TrevorAnderson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6677541/rewinding-the-charts-15-years-ago-janet-jackson-scored-a-hot-100|title=Rewinding the Charts: 15 Years Ago, Janet Jackson Scored a Hot 100 First|last=Anderson|first=Trevor|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=August 26, 2015|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe track peaked at number two on the [[Rhythmic Top 40]],<ref name=\"Rhythmic\"/> number three on [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] and [[Mainstream Top 40]],<ref name=\"USR&B\"/><ref name=\"Top40\"/> and at number nine on the [[Hot Dance Singles Sales]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZhAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA31&#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Hot Dance Music \u2013 Maxi Singles Sales \u2013 August 26, 2000|magazine=Billboard|volume=112|number=35|page=31|date=August 26, 2000|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> It also registered a 75-1 climb on the [[Hot Singles Sales]] chart, after debuting before its physical release because of street date violations.<ref name=\"Spotlight\"/> \"Doesn't Really Matter\" was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) on September 25, 2000, for selling 500,000 copies in the US.<ref name=\"RIAA\"/> According to the RIAA, Jackson became the third female singer, after Madonna and [[Whitney Houston]], to achieve 19 gold-selling singles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/newsitem.php?id=8FE9018F-4FD8-8A99-C464-ED5774E23BF3|title=Diamonds Are a 'Chicks' Best Friend|publisher=Recording Industry Association of America|access-date=February 7, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221215851/https://www.riaa.com/newsitem.php?id=8FE9018F-4FD8-8A99-C464-ED5774E23BF3|archive-date=February 21, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The song was the 13th best-selling single of 2000 in the US with sales of 600,000 copies (rounded off to the nearest 100,000).<ref name=\"Sales\"/>\n\nIn Canada, \"Doesn't Really Matter\" debuted at number 45 on the ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top 100 Singles chart dated July 3, 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/item.aspx?IdNumber=5054&|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 5054|website=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|via=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> On the October 2 issue, it peaked at number two, being kept from the top spot by Madonna's \"Music\".<ref name=\"can\"/> In Australia, the song bowed at number 28 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"AU\"/> On the [[New Zealand Singles Chart]], it peaked at number 27 and spent a total of six weeks on the chart.<ref name=\"NZ\"/> \"Doesn't Really Matter\" fared better on the [[UK Singles Chart]] where it debuted at number five, making it Jackson's 15th single to reach the top 10 in the UK.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://scans.chartarchive.org/UK/2000/UK%20Charts%202000.08.19.pdf|title=Chart Commentary|last=Jones|first=Alan|magazine=[[Music Week]]|date=August 19, 2000|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The song was present on the chart for 11 weeks and was certified silver by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI) for selling 200,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/42628/janet-jackson/|title=Janet Jackson - Artist|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"UKCert\"/> In Europe, \"Doesn't Really Matter\" charted in the top 10 in Denmark, Italy, Poland and Spain.<ref name=\"Denmark\"/><ref name=\"Italy\"/><ref name=\"Poland\"/><ref name=\"Spain\"/> It also reached the top 20 in Belgium (Wallonia), the Netherlands, Norway, Sweden, and Switzerland.<ref name=\"Wallonia\"/><ref name=\"Dutch100\"/><ref name=\"Norway\"/><ref name=\"Sweden\"/><ref name=\"Switzerland\"/> In Japan, \"Doesn't Really Matter\" received a [[Japan Gold Disc Award]] from the [[Recording Industry Association of Japan]] (RIAJ) for Top Selling Song of the Year by a foreign artist.<ref name=\"RIAJ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/e/data/gdisc/2001.html|title=Recording Industry Association of Japan \u2013 Related Data|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of Japan]]|access-date=April 12, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031220134721/http://www.riaj.or.jp/e/data/gdisc/2001.html|archive-date=December 20, 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n===Background===\n{{multiple image|align=right\n|total_width=328\n|image1=Akihabara Night.jpg\n|image2=Sony, aibo (cane robot), anni 2000 (ist. biorobotica polo sant'anna valdera).jpg\n|footer=The music video for \"Doesn't Really Matter\" is inspired by several elements from Japan, such as the video's futuristic setting, and the [[AIBO]] that is seen near Jackson.\n}}\nThe music video for \"Doesn't Really Matter\" was directed by [[Joseph Kahn]], with the setting portraying a futuristic city inspired by Tokyo. It showcases Jackson in an [[abstract art|abstract]] [[anime]]-based environment, featuring an [[AIBO]], which was the very first consumer Artificial Intelligence robot and was created for the companionship of adults and elderly people. Morphing clothes, levitating platforms, and a futuristic [[Acura]] vehicle, the [[Acura CL]]-X Concept Prototype, are featured in the video.<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/> The music video was filmed in [[Universal City, California]] on June 4\u20135, and premiered on [[MTV]]'s ''[[Making the Video]]'' on June 28, 2000.<ref name=\"Making\">{{cite episode|title=Janet Jackson: Doesn't Really Matter|series=[[Making the Video]]|network=[[MTV]]|date=June 28, 2000|season=3|number=2|language=en}}</ref> Production costs were over $2.5 million\n(equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|2.5|2000|r=1}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}), making it one of the [[list of most expensive music videos|most expensive music videos]] of all time.<ref name=\"NewYorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/11/20/janet-jacksons-doesnt-really-matter-music-video-saw-the-future?verso=true|title=Janet Jackson's \"Doesn't Really Matter\" Music Video Saw The Future|last=Trammell|first=Matthew|website=The New Yorker|date=November 10, 2017|access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"HighSnob\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/most-expensive-music-videos/|title=The 5 Artists With the Most Expensive Music Videos of All Time|last=Bather|first=Luke|website=[[Highsnobiety]]|date=June 2, 2015|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nKahn described the video's premise as \"epic minimalism\" in an attempt to differentiate from the large sets of other music videos airing during the same time. He wanted to use minimal sets that would appear larger.<ref name=\"Making\" /> Jackson contacted Kahn to direct the music video,<ref name=\"Kahn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.njs4ever.net/kahn3.html|title=An Interview With Joseph Kahn \u2013 Page Three|work=Peel|date=July 2000|access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> explaining that she wanted to experiment with make-up and costuming in order to take risks.<ref name=\"Making\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videostatic.com/interviews/2014/01/07/videostatic-interview-joseph-kahn|title=Talking Videos, Britney and more with Director Joseph Kahn|last=Gottlieb|first=Stephen|website=Video Static|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> One of the dancers, [[Jenna Dewan]], received the role in the music video at the age of 19 as the only spot the choreographers were looking for in an audition.<ref name=\"JennaDewan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8456679/jenna-dewan-janet-jackson-dancer-interview|title=Jenna Dewan on the Life-Changing Impact of Working With Janet Jackson: 'Once a Janet Dancer, Always a Janet Dancer'|last=Milzoff|first=Rebecca|website=Billboard|url-access=subscription|date=May 18, 2018|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> All the dancers performed choreography on a moving platform while harnessed on bungee cords.<ref name=\"JennaDewan\"/> The platform was implemented to tilt and slant, which would cause Jackson and the dancers to slide and fall off.<ref name=\"Making\" /> The original scene was designed on a set, but was taken apart and replaced with a [[Chroma key|green screen]].<ref name=\"Making\"/>\n\nThe music video was one of the first appearances by Dewan, who stated \"I was fortunate enough to work with Janet who treats her dancers amazing\".<ref name=\"JennaDewan\"/> Following the video shoot, Jackson asked Dewan to appear in the music video for her 2001 single \"[[All for You (Janet Jackson song)|All for You]]\", and be a dancer on her two-year [[All for You Tour]].<ref name=\"JennaDewan\"/>\n\n===Synopsis===\nThe video opens with a postcard, featuring the song's title and Jackson's name, drifting on a sidewalk and being stepped on by pedestrians. It then pans from a panoramic nighttime city view to a scene of Jackson singing from her bed in a confined apartment. During this scene, the AIBO and various objects in her room are shown, including a television displaying ''Nutty Professor II: The Klumps'', and a pair of [[moon shoes]]. Jackson then grabs a beverage from her fridge and starts singing in front of a mirror containing visually animated animal stickers. Four of her friends knock at her door and Jackson leaves with them. They dance through the apartment block hallway as their shoes morph into black futuristic high-heels, walking into an area filled with display screens and a circular platform.\n\nDuring the song's breakdown, they perform a choreographed dance routine on the tilting platform. The scenes are intercut with Jackson drawing an orange swirl and the AIBO watching the film in her apartment. Various people are also seen drawing orange swirls. In the next segment, Jackson is shown in the passenger seat of a car driving through a tunnel, as scenes from ''Nutty Professor II: The Klumps'' appear as a reflection in the front window. The video concludes with a [[slow motion]] shot of Jackson falling backwards onto her bed and the AIBO resting in front of her.\n\n===Reception===\nWriting for DVD Movie Guide, Colin Jacobson praised the music video for deviating from the standard \"lip-synch/film snippet formula\" used among pop videos at the time, stating that it \"stands on its own\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdmg.com/klumpsuncensored.shtml|title=Nutty Professor II: The Klumps \u2013 Uncensored Director's Cut (2000)|website=DVD Movie Guide|last=Jacobson|first=Colin|year=2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Rod Stafford Hagwood of the ''Sun-Sentinel'' included \"Doesn't Really Matter\" among several videos which set fashion trends and increased the popularity of \"bright colorful clothes\" among youth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2000-08-08/lifestyle/0008070457_1_colors-young-women-video|title=What Are The Coolest Kids Wearing This Fall? Fiery Reds And Blazing Oranges Because They Are . . .|website=Sun-Sentinel|last=Hagwood|first=Rod Stafford|date=August 8, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Aaron Beierle of [[DVD Talk]] likened the video's setting to [[science fiction film]] ''[[The Fifth Element]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/1275/nutty-professor-2-the-klumps/|title=Nutty Professor 2: The Klumps : DVD Talk Review of the DVD Video|website=[[DVD Talk]]|last=Beierle|first=Aaron|date=November 11, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>  Matthew Trammell of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' wrote that it is \"one of the most forward-leaning music videos of its time\".<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/> However, Luke Bather of ''[[Highsnobiety]]'' was critical of the music video, calling the [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] \"primitive\" and describing how it portrays a [[dystopia]]n future where everyone feels \"bizarrely happy\" while only being able to watch ''The Nutty Professor'' on television.<ref name=\"HighSnob\"/>\n\n==Live performances==\nJackson performed \"Doesn't Really Matter\" on the August 4, 2000 episode of the British music chart television program ''[[Top of the Pops]]''.<ref>{{cite episode|series=[[Top of the Pops]]|network=[[BBC One]]|series-number=37|number=32|date=August 4, 2000|language=en}}</ref> She also performed the song at the [[2000 MTV Video Music Awards]] on September 7, opening the show from a three-tiered aerial set with 10 backing dancers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Style Beats Substance Among Artists At Video Music Awards|magazine=The Orlando Sentinel|last=Abott|first=Jim|date=September 8, 2000}}</ref> Jackson wore a black leather outfit and her long hair obscured her face most of the performance.<ref name=\"VMAs\">{{cite web|last=Basham|first=David|url=http://www.sonicnet.com:80/artists/ai_singlestory.jhtml?id=1123893&ai_id=1090|title=VMA Report #2: Janet Jackson Kicks Off Night's Performances|website=MTV News|via=Sonicnet|accessdate=December 27, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001209075800/http://www.sonicnet.com/artists/ai_singlestory.jhtml?id=1123893&ai_id=1090|archivedate=December 9, 2000|url-status=dead}}</ref> Jeff Stark of ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' found the dance routine \"elaborate\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2000/09/08/mtv_awards_2/|title=Rock is dead and well at the MTV Video Awards|last=Stark|first=Jeff|website=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|date=September 8, 2000|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' included the performance in its 2015 list of 10 Iconic Janet Jackson Performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vibe.com/photos/iconic-janet-jackson-performances|title=Under One Rhythm Nation: 10 Iconic Janet Jackson Performances|last=Braboy|first=Mark|website=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|date=June 27, 2015|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe song was also performed during the [[encore]] of the All for You Tour. The renditions were viewed as more intimate in contrast to the spectacle of earlier performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/ms-janet-jackson-gets-nasty-20010710|title=Ms. Janet Jackson Gets Nasty|last=Sheppard|first=Denise|website=Rolling Stone|date=July 10, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2001-10-26/entertainment/0110240916_1_jackson-s-new-music-janet-jackson-tours/2|title=Just Call Her The Diva Next Door|website=Sun-Sentinel|last=Gamboa|first=Glenn|date=October 26, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/janet-find-article-1.932368#ixzz2tCK2UlPc|title=Janet's All For You, If You Can Find Her|website=New York Daily News|last=Farber|first=Jim|date=August 21, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> \"Doesn't Really Matter\" was also performed during Jackson's 2008 [[Rock Witchu Tour]], her first concert tour in six years.<ref>{{cite website|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/janet-jackson-opens-rock-witchu-tour-with-three-decades-of-hits-video-duets-and-pyro-20080911|title=Janet Jackson Opens Rock Witchu Tour With Three Decades of Hits|date=September 11, 2008|accessdate=September 9, 2014|last=Sheppard|first=Denise|website=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref> She insisted on the tour being \"dance-heavy\" after fans left messages on Jackson's [[phone-in]] number, which was used by Jackson to directly communicate with them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbsun.com/2008/09/11/janet-jackson-still-singin-still-dancin-still-witchu/|title=Janet Jackson still singin', still dancin', stil witchu|author=The Sun|website=[[The San Bernardino Sun]]|date=September 11, 2008|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> During Jackson's 2011 [[Number Ones, Up Close and Personal]] tour, the song was performed in a [[Medley (music)|medley]] with \"[[Escapade (song)|Escapade]]\", \"[[Love Will Never Do (Without You)]]\", \"[[When I Think of You]]\" and \"All for You\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/21/arts/music/janet-jacksons-number-ones-at-radio-city-review.html?_r=1&|title=Janet Jackson's 'Number Ones' at Radio City|website=[[The New York Times]]|last=Ratliff|first=Ben|date=March 20, 2011|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> The music video appeared on screen before the start of the concert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ocregister.com/soundcheck/ocregister-481692-http-soundcheck.html|title=Janet Jackson in top form heading into L.A. gigs|last=Wener|first=Ben|website=[[Orange County Register]]|date=April 11, 2011|access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> The song was also included in the set lists for the second leg of Jackson's 2018 [[State of the World Tour]], and her 2019 Las Vegas residency, [[Janet Jackson: Metamorphosis]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Herbert|first=Geoff|title=Janet Jackson turns Syracuse into dance party with a message|url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2018/07/janet_jackson_syracuse_concert_review.html|date=August 10, 2018|website=Scene|access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mitchell|first=Gail|title=Janet Jackson Draws Queen Latifah, Eve & More to ''Metamorphosis'' Residency Opening in Las Vegas |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8512088/janet-jackson-metamorphosis-las-vegas-residency-opening-review|website=Billboard|date=May 20, 2019|access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cover versions==\nPuerto Rican flautist [[N\u00e9stor Torres]] recorded a [[jazz]] version of \"Doesn't Really Matter\"  for his seventh album, ''This Side of Paradise'', released on March 13, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/this-side-of-paradise-mw0000115719|title=This Side of Paradise - Nestor Torres|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2002-08-26/news/0208260048_1_nestor-torres-latin-grammy-band|title=A Romantic, Energetic Evening From Nestor Torres|last=Bowser|first=Andre J.|website=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=August 26, 2002|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> \n\nJapanese singer [[Hitomi Shimatani]] covered the song under the title \"Papillon\" for her [[Papillon (Hitomi Shimatani album)|2001 debut album of the same name]].<ref name=\"Avex\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jpopasia.com/celebrity/hitomishimatani/|title=Hitomi Shimatani's bio \u2013 singer \u2013 jpop|website=JPopAsia|year=January 2007|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Jackson initially prevented Shimatani's label [[Avex Trax]] from shipping the CD because the lyrics differed from Jackson's image of the song.<ref name=\"sponichi 20010206\"/> She finally allowed the CD's release after a month's negotiation, stating that she appreciated seeing a new aspect of \"Doesn't Really Matter\" arranged in an Asian style.<ref name=\"sponichi 20010206\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sponichi.co.jp/entertainment/kiji/2001/02/06/03.html|title=\u30b8\u30e3\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8 \u30ab\u30d0\u30fc\u66f2\u304a\u8535\u5165\u308a\u5bf8\u524d\u5fa9\u6d3b|language=Japanese|website=[[Sports Nippon|Sponichianex]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010210071747/http://www.sponichi.co.jp/entertainment/kiji/2001/02/06/03.html|archive-date=February 10, 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref> The song's [[katakana]] lyrics include [[Orient|oriental]] themes such as [[Nelumbo nucifera|lotus flowers]], gods, beliefs, dreams, and smiles.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.505.3487&rep=rep1&type=pdf|title=Cultural Reinterpretation of Popular Music: The Case of Japanese/American Cover Songs|last=Yoneoka|first=Judy|journal=Kyushu Communication Studies|volume=6|pages=23\u201341|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The single was released on February 7, 2001, and peaked at number 14 on Japan's [[Oricon Singles Chart]] where it charted for 23 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/music/release/d/412539/1/|title=Papillon ~ papillon ~ / Hitomi Shimatani|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Oricon]]|access-date=April 10, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022131021/http://www.oricon.co.jp/music/release/d/412539/1/|archive-date=October 22, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The song sold over 200,000 copies in Japan, making Shimatani one of Avex Trax's most successful singers at the time.<ref name=\"Avex\"/> An eastern butterfly version was later issued on the song's [[maxi single|maxi]] release on June 27, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/240400/products/450106/1/|title=Papillon ~ papillon ~ / Hitomi Shimatani|language=Japanese|publisher=Oricon|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''[[CD single]]'''<ref name=\"LinerNotes\"/>\n{{Track listing |title_width=30em\n| title1        = Doesn't Really Matter (Radio Edit)\n| length1       = 4:18\n| title2        = Doesn't Really Matter ([[Jonathan Peters]] Club Mix)\n| length2       = 8:49\n}}\n\n'''US [[12-inch single]]'''<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=Doesn't Really Matter|others=Janet Jackson|year=2000|type=back cover|publisher=Def Jam Records|id=314 562 828-1|location=New York City}}</ref>\n{{Track listing |title_width=30em\n| headline      = Side A\n| title1        = Doesn't Really Matter ([[Rockwilder]] Mix)\n| length1       = 5:41\n| title2        = Doesn't Really Matter (Jonathan Peters Club Mix)\n| length2       = 8:49\n| title3         = Doesn't Really Matter (Spensane Get Up Extended Mix)\n| length3       = 6:30\n}} \n{{Track listing |title_width=30em\n| headline       = Side B\n| title1         = Doesn't Really Matter (Rockwilder Instrumental)\n| length1       = 4:59\n| title2         = Doesn't Really Matter (Jonathan Peters Sound Factory Dub Mix)\n| length2       = 6:34\n| title3         = Doesn't Really Matter (Spensane Get Up Dub Mix)\n| length3       = 4:32\n}}\n\n'''US [[cassette single]]'''<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=Doesn't Really Matter|others=Janet Jackson|year=2000|type=booklet|publisher=Def Jam Records|id=314 562 846-4|location=New York City}}</ref>\n{{Track listing |title_width=30em\n| headline      = Side A\n| title1        = Doesn't Really Matter (Album Versio